--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;lranatunga&quot; &lt;lranatun@s...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I too am relatively new to junit, but try the following revision:
&gt; 
&gt; public class TestProject
&gt;     extends TestSuite {
&gt; 
&gt;   //...
&gt; 
&gt;   public static Test suite() {
&gt;     TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt; 
&gt;     //---instead of this:
&gt;     //suite.addTestSuite(dk.company.emc.TestPackage.class);
&gt; 
&gt;     //---try this:
&gt;     suite.addTest(dk.company.emc.TestPackage.suite());
&gt; 
&gt;     return suite;
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Note that the above:
&gt; 1. uses addTest() instead of addTestSuite()
&gt; 2. calls the TestPackage.suite() static method which returns a Test.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Also, btw, if your package level suite only has a single TestCase, 
you
&gt; can use the following shortcut:
&gt; 
&gt; public static Test suite() {
&gt;   return new TestSuite(dk.company.emc.TestPackage.class);
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; instead of:
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; public static Test suite() {
&gt; &gt;   TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt; &gt;   suite.addTestSuite(dk.company.emc.TestPackage.class);
&gt; &gt;   return suite;
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; cheers.
&gt; 
